Europe needs immigration to restart
BRUSSELS — More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
Meanwhile, the rescue ship Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching for safe ports to land their passengers all summer.
The refugee and migrant camps on the Greek island of Lesvos are overflowing, as are other accommodation centers in Libya.
Turkey has撕毁ed the 2016 agreement that aimed to prevent migrants from entering the EU.
Despite Europe's desire to help migrants and its respect for international law, it does not want to be overpopulated.
In 2015-16, the number of refugees and migrants entering the EU surged – many fleeing the Syrian war – which greatly eroded trust within the EU.
The massive inflow of migrants eroded government confidence in managing external EU borders and asylum, and highlighted the ineffectiveness of cooperation with countries of origin.
Thus, migration has become a political football, a boon to populists.
Under President von der Leyen's leadership, the new EU Commission must reassert control over migration while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this, the EU needs to rework four key approaches, mobilizing member states to act in the interest of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping its internal borders open.
No country where people can freely move around internally – including the US, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia – would outsource border control to a state or region.
Controlling the EU’s external borders must be a collective task as well as a national one.
The EU Border and Coast Guard Frontex must be further strengthened and should deploy joint task forces with member states – including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal migration in the Mediterranean.
Second, Europe needs to address economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Mixing them has already brought the asylum system close to collapse; separating them would help ensure that migrants concerned for their safety can be heard with their rights protected.
Addressing the EU’s genuine economic and social needs requires effective blue or green card policies for economic migrants and the implementation of overall immigration targets.
This must not wait until the next migration crisis to consider introducing such mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break taboos.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a common interest issue.
Second, policies must clearly define which migrants are desirable.
Third, member states must identify what kind of EU assistance is needed to facilitate smooth migration processes.
Finally, visas and work permits must be put on the table to facilitate the return of illegal immigrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaty, each member state is responsible for managing migration from outside the EU.
But agreeing on overall EU migration targets would be a significant step forward.
In return, member states could specify the economic migrant source countries they want and their specific requirements, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
This way, the right to accept migrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has had an active immigration policy for decades, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skills, and age.
Europe could do this too.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, it must abandon the one-size-fits-all requirement for mandatory distribution of asylum seekers within the EU.
This requirement undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but could still be feasible if the border, asylum, and migration systems were fully effective.
In addition, it cannot be expected that frontline member states of the EU alone will resolve the issue of illegal migration crossing external borders.
Camps are already overflowing, and migrants are either abused by authorities or pushed northward.
The responsibility of the first member state that migrants arrive in must be supplemented by EU solidarity.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to streamline the behavior and management capacity of national asylum agencies.
Only then can national decisions be respected across the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the area for cross-border travel.
After streamlining the behavior and management capacity of national asylum agencies, the processing of asylum applications can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build stronger win-win cooperation with origin and transit countries.
To deport migrants who are legally barred from entering the EU back to their home countries, these connections are crucial.
To ensure such cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's migration objectives, and skill cooperation to prepare for jobs in Europe, can be offered to third countries that desire stable remittances.
Meanwhile, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes the population explosion in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; racial conflicts; and shortages of work opportunities.
The EU's assistance should focus on rebuilding stability and reducing risks through supporting safety, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area could make investments safer, release private and domestic finance, and achieve national economic growth, job creation, and alternative migration options.
This new approach by the EU Commission offers a chance for the EU to move away from an unconscious reaction to the migration crisis and toward a consistent and sustainable policy both internally and externally, avoiding missed opportunities.
We must not miss this opportunity.
